04334nam a22005295i 9780773589438DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20132013xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735894387 a10.1515/97807735894382doi  a(DE-B1597)655720  a(OCoLC)862010018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aF1035.A1bF67 2014eb 7aSOC0200002bisacsh04a305.8223  aME 88002rvk0(DE-625)rvk/122639:1 aFoster, Cecil, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGenuine Multiculturalism :bThe Tragedy and Comedy of Diversity /cCecil Foster. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (496 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: The Tragedy of Living, the Comedy of Trying -- tNatural Differences and Social Equality -- tGenuine Multiculturalism -- tDramatis personae -- tPractices Against Social Diversity -- tA Hegelian – Christian Model -- tMulticulturalism in the Americas -- tCanada’s Second Covenant: The Charter of Rights -- tWhen Tragedy Becomes Comedy -- tThe Legacy of the US Civil War -- tCanada: Forging a Single Consciousness -- tCitizenship with Difference: The CBC and I -- tCrisis 2001: Not Enough People! -- tMassey and Culture: From Bi to Multi -- tAccepting Diversity, Promoting Social Equality -- tTyranny v. Freedom: Strauss v. Kojève -- tRawls and Trudeau’s Just Society -- tRethinking the CBC and Me: From Tragedy to Comedy -- tTragedy: The Comedic Folk Saviour -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile many modern societies are noted for their diversity, the resulting challenge is to determine how citizens from different backgrounds and cultures can see themselves and each other as equals, and be treated equally. In Genuine Multiculturalism, Cecil Foster shows that a society's failure to bridge these differences is the tragedy of modern living and that pretending it is possible to mechanically develop fraternity and solidarity among diverse groups is akin to seeking out comedy. Arguing that genuine multiculturalism is the search for social justice by individuals who have been trapped by ascribed identities or newcomers who have been shut out of perceived ethnic homelands, Foster details how this process, in essence, is the story of the Americas. Reconceptionalizing the terms of multiculturalism, he offers an intervention into Canada's claim that its definition and practice are based on recognizing equality of citizenship. Identifying genuine multiculturalism as an ongoing work in progress, rather than a tightly defined policy position, Foster challenges readers to imagine a greater and more harmonious ideal. A necessary theoretical reconsideration of diversity within society, Genuine Multiculturalism refocuses the debate about ideals and practices in modern societies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMulticulturalismzCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Minority Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077358943840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773589438423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773589438/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles